  "transcript": [
    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 18.9,
      "end": 26.26,
      "text": "A fir tree was boasting to a bramble and said, somewhat contemptuously, you poor creature,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 26.26,
      "end": 32.5,
      "text": "you have no use whatsoever. Now look at me, I am useful for all sorts of things,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 32.98,
      "end": 36.82,
      "text": "particularly when men build houses. They can't do without me then.\"",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 38.62,
      "end": 39.8,
      "text": "But the bramble replied,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 40.76,
      "end": 45.48,
      "text": "ah, that's all very well, but you wait till they come with axes and saws to cut you down,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 45.98,
      "end": 48.66,
      "text": "and then you'll wish you were a bramble, and not a fir.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 50.36,
      "end": 57.46,
      "text": "The moral? Better poverty without a care than wealth with its many obligations.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 62.16,
      "end": 66.44,
      "text": "This has been an audio recording of the fir and the bramble from ASOP's Fables,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 66.94,
      "end": 71.06,
      "text": "read by Andy Fluke of 13pennies.net for LibriVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
